        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000139": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000139",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><h2><a></a>PART I.</h2></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000140": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000140",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\">\n\n</div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000141": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000141",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><h2><a></a>CHAPTER II.</h2></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000142": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000142",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><h3>ON THE ACQUISITION OF DHARMA, ARTHA AND KAMA.</h3></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000143": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000143",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Man, the period of whose life is one hundred years, should practise Dharma, Artha, and Kama at different times and in such a manner that they may harmonize together and not clash in any way. He should acquire learning in his childhood, in his youth and middle age he should attend to Artha and Kama, and in his old age he should perform Dharma, and thus seek to gain Moksha, <i>i.e.</i>, release from further transmigration. Or, on account of the uncertainty of life, he may practise them at times when they are enjoined to be practised. But one thing is to be noted, he should lead the life of a religious student until he finishes his education.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000144": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000144",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p><i>Dharma</i> is obedience to the command of the Shastra or Holy Writ of the Hindoos to do certain things, such as the performance of sacrifices, which are not generally done because they do not belong to this world, and produce no visible effect; and not to do other things, such as eating meat, which is often done because it belongs to this world, and has visible effects.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000145": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000145",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Dharma should be learnt from the Shruti (Holy Writ), and from those conversant with it.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000146": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000146",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p><i>Artha</i> is the acquisition of arts, land, gold, cattle, wealth, equipages and friends. It is, further, the protection of what is acquired, and the increase of what is protected.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000147": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000147",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Artha should be learnt from the king's officers, and from merchants who may be versed in the ways of commerce.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000148": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000148",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p><i>Kama</i> is the enjoyment of appropriate objects by the five senses of hearing, feeling, seeing, tasting, and smelling, assisted by the mind together with the soul. The ingredient in this is a peculiar contact between the organ of sense and its object, and the consciousness of pleasure which arises from that contact is called Kama.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000149": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000149",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p><a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>Kama is to be learnt from the Kama Sutra (aphorisms on love) and from the practice of citizens.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000150": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000150",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>When all the three, viz., Dharma, Artha, and Kama come together, the former is better than the one which follows it, <i>i.e.</i>, Dharma is better than Artha, and Artha is better than Kama. But Artha should be always first practised by the king, for the livelihood of men is to be obtained from it only. Again, Kama being the occupation of public women, they should prefer it to the other two, and these are exceptions to the general rule.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000151": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000151",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Objection 1.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000152": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000152",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Some learned men say that as Dharma is connected with things not belonging to this world, it is appropriately treated of in a book; and so also is Artha, because it is practised only by the application of proper means, and a knowledge of those means can only be obtained by study and from books. But Kama being a thing which is practised even by the brute creation, and which is to be found everywhere, does not want any work on the subject.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000153": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000153",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Answer.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000154": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000154",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>This is not so. Sexual intercourse being a thing dependent on man and woman requires the application of proper means by them, and those means are to be learnt from the Kama Shastra. The non-application of proper means, which we see in the brute creation, is caused by their being unrestrained, and by the females among them only being fit for sexual intercourse at certain seasons and no more, and by their intercourse not being preceded by thought of any kind.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000155": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000155",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Objection 2.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000156": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000156",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>The Lokayatikas<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002134\">[4]</$link> say:—Religious ordinances should not be observed, for they bear a future fruit, and at the same time it is also doubtful whether they will bear any fruit at all. What foolish person will give away that which is in his own hands<a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a> into the hands of another? Moreover, it is better to have a pigeon to-day than a peacock to-morrow; and a copper coin which we have the certainty of obtaining, is better than a gold coin, the possession of which is doubtful.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000157": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000157",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Answer.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000158": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000158",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>It is not so. 1st. Holy Writ, which ordains the practice of Dharma, does not admit of a doubt.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000159": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000159",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>2nd. Sacrifices such as those made for the destruction of enemies, or for the fall of rain, are seen to bear fruit.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000160": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000160",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>3rd. The sun, moon, stars, planets and other heavenly bodies appear to work intentionally for the good of the world.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000161": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000161",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>4th. The existence of this world is effected by the observance of the rules respecting the four classes<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002138\">[5]</$link> of men and their four stages of life.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000162": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000162",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>5th. We see that seed is thrown into the ground with the hope of future crops.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000163": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000163",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Vatsyayana is therefore of opinion that the ordinances of religion must be obeyed.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000164": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000164",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Objection 3.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000165": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000165",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Those who believe that destiny is the prime mover of all things say:—We should not exert ourselves to acquire wealth, for sometimes it is not acquired although we strive to get it, while at other times it comes to us of itself without any exertion on our part. Everything is therefore in the power of destiny, who is the lord of gain and loss, of success and defeat, of pleasure and pain. Thus we see the Bali<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002142\">[6]</$link> was raised to the throne of Indra by destiny, and was also put down by the same power, and it is destiny only that can re-instate him.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000166": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000166",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Answer.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000167": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000167",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>It is not right to say so. As the acquisition of every object <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>pre-supposes at all events some exertion on the part of man, the application of proper means may be said to be the cause of gaining all our ends, and this application of proper means being thus necessary (even where a thing is destined to happen), it follows that a person who does nothing will enjoy no happiness.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000168": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000168",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Objection 4.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000169": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000169",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Those who are inclined to think that Artha is the chief object to be obtained argue thus. Pleasures should not be sought for, because they are obstacles to the practice of Dharma and Artha, which are both superior to them, and are also disliked by meritorious persons. Pleasures also bring a man into distress, and into contact with low persons; they cause him to commit unrighteous deeds, and produce impurity in him; they make him regardless of the future, and encourage carelessness and levity. And lastly, they cause him to be disbelieved by all, received by none, and despised by everybody, including himself. It is notorious, moreover, that many men who have given themselves up to pleasure alone, have been ruined along with their families and relations. Thus, King Dandakya,<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002146\">[7]</$link> of the Bhoja dynasty, carried off a Brahman's daughter with evil intent, and was eventually ruined and lost his kingdom. Indra, too, having violated the chastity of Ahalya,<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002150\">[8]</$link> was made to suffer for it. In a like manner the mighty Kichaka,<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002154\">[9]</$link> who tried to seduce Draupadi, and Ravana,<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002158\">[10]</$link> who attempted to gain over Sita, were punished for their <a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>crimes. These and many others fell by reason of their pleasures.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000170": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000170",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p class=\"center\"><i>Answer.</i></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000171": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000171",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>This objection cannot be sustained, for pleasures, being as necessary for the existence and well being of the body as food, are consequently equally required. They are, moreover, the results of Dharma and Artha. Pleasures are, therefore, to be followed with moderation and caution. No one refrains from cooking food because there are beggars to ask for it, or from sowing seed because there are deer to destroy the corn when it is grown up.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000172": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000172",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Thus a man practising Dharma, Artha and Kama enjoys happiness both in this world and in the world to come. The good perform those actions in which there is no fear as to what is to result from them in the next world, and in which there is no danger to their welfare. Any action which conduces to the practice of Dharma, Artha and Kama together, or of any two, or even one of them, should be performed, but an action which conduces to the practice of one of them at the expense of the remaining two should not be performed.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000173": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000173",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\">\n\n</div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000174": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000174",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p><a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a></p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000175": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000175",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><h2><a></a>CHAPTER III.</h2></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000176": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000176",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><h3>ON THE ARTS AND SCIENCES TO BE STUDIED.</h3></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000177": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000177",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Man should study the Kama Sutra and the arts and sciences subordinate thereto, in addition to the study of the arts and sciences contained in Dharma and Artha. Even young maids should study this Kama Sutra along with its arts and sciences before marriage, and after it they should continue to do so with the consent of their husbands.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000178": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000178",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>Here some learned men object, and say that females, not being allowed to study any science, should not study the Kama Sutra.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000179": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000179",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>But Vatsyayana is of opinion that this objection does not hold good, for women already know the practice of Kama Sutra, and that practice is derived from the Kama Shastra, or the science of Kama itself. Moreover, it is not only in this but in many other cases that though the practice of a science is known to all, only a few persons are acquainted with the rules and laws on which the science is based. Thus the Yadnikas or sacrificers, though ignorant of grammar, make use of appropriate words when addressing the different Deities, and do not know how these words are framed. Again, persons do the duties required of them on auspicious days, which are fixed by astrology, though they are not acquainted with the science of astrology. In a like manner riders of horses and elephants train these animals without knowing the science of training animals, but from practice only. And similarly the people of the most distant provinces obey the laws of the kingdom from practice, and because there is a king over them, and without further reason.<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002162\">[11]</$link> And from experience we find that some women, such as daughters of princes and their ministers, and public women, are actually versed in the Kama Shastra.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000180": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000180",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p><a class=\"x-ebookmaker-pageno\"></a>A female, therefore, should learn the Kama Shastra, or at least a part of it, by studying its practice from some confidential friend. She should study alone in private the sixty-four practices that form a part of the Kama Shastra. Her teacher should be one of the following persons, viz., the daughter of a nurse brought up with her and already married,<a></a><$link class=\"fnanchor pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002166\">[12]</$link> or a female friend who can be trusted in everything, or the sister of her mother (<i>i.e.</i>, her aunt), or an old female servant, or a female beggar who may have formerly lived in the family, or her own sister, who can always be trusted.</p></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000181": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000000181",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><p>The following are the arts to be studied, together with the Kama Sutra:—</p></div>"
        },
