        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002309": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002309",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002310": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002310",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001072\"><span class=\"label\">[48]</span></$link> These last few lines have been exemplified in many ways in many novels of this century.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002311": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002311",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002312": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002312",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002313": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002313",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002314": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002314",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001098\"><span class=\"label\">[49]</span></$link> There is a good deal of truth in the last few observations. Woman is a <a></a><$link class=\"correction pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002556\">monogamous</$link> animal, and loves but one, and likes to feel herself alone in the affections of one man, and cannot bear rivals. It may also be taken as a general rule that women either married to, or kept by, rich men love them for their wealth, but not for themselves.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002315": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002315",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002316": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002316",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002317": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002317",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002318": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002318",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001102\"><span class=\"label\">[50]</span></$link> These forms of marriage differ from the four kinds of marriage mentioned in Chapter <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001016\">I</$link>., and are only to be made use of when the girl is gained over in the way mentioned in Chapters <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001075\">III</$link>. and <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001087\">IV</$link>.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002319": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002319",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002320": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002320",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002321": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002321",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002322": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002322",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001103\"><span class=\"label\">[51]</span></$link> About this, see a story on the fatal effects of love at page 114 of &quot;Early Ideas; a Group of Hindoo Stories,&quot; collected and collated by Anaryan. W. H. Allen and Co., London, 1881.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002323": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002323",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002324": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002324",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002325": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002325",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002326": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002326",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001114\"><span class=\"label\">[52]</span></$link> About the Gandharvavivaha form of marriage, see note to page 28 of Captain R. F. Burton's &quot;Vickram and the Vampire; or Tales of Hindu Devilry.&quot; Longman, Green &amp; Co., London, 1870. This form of matrimony was recognised by the ancient Hindus, and is frequent in books. It is a kind of Scotch Wedding—ultra-Caledonian—taking place by mutual consent without any form or ceremony. The Gandharvas are heavenly minstrels of Indra's court, who are supposed to be witnesses,</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002327": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002327",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002328": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002328",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002329": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002329",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002330": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002330",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001134\"><span class=\"label\">[53]</span></$link> This probably refers to a girl married in her infancy, or when very young, and whose husband had died before she arrived at the age of puberty. Infant marriages are still the common custom of the Hindoos.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002331": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002331",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002332": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002332",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002333": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002333",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002334": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002334",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001164\"><span class=\"label\">[54]</span></$link> A name given to the maid servants of the zenana of the Kings in ancient times, on account of their always keeping their breasts covered with a cloth called Kanchuki. It was customary in the olden time for the maid servants to cover their breasts with a cloth, while the Queens kept their breasts uncovered. This custom is distinctly to be seen in the Ajunta cave paintings.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002335": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002335",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002336": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002336",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002337": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002337",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002338": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002338",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-e24e33 twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-ee4fbb twpub-ca7bc903db05ca3e-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000001164\"><span class=\"label\">[55]</span></$link> The meaning of this word is a superior woman, so it would seem that a Mahallarika must be a person in authority over the maid servants of the house.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002339": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/ca7bc903db05ca3e/text/000002339",
